mbitious in its scope yet straightforward in its approach, Lawyer Nation seeks to address these crises by offering a path forward for the legal profession. Ray Brescia provides concrete ideas for transforming law into a field whose services are accessible, egalitarian, and viable in the long term. Further, he addresses how the profession can improve so that the health of its practitioners is not compromised in the process. If the legal profession does not respond to its crises in an effective way, he argues, the dysfunction and unfairness plaguing the legal world will deepen. This is an unprecedented opportunity for the world of law to reimagine its future in way that honors its highest ideals: preserving the rule of law, protecting individual liberty, and addressing social inequality in all of its forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLawyerszUnited States. 0aPractice of lawzUnited States. 7aLAW / Legal Profession.2bisacsh  a#MeToo.  aA Values-Based Profession.  aAccess to Justice.  aAlexander Hamilton.  aAlexis de Tocqueville.  aAmerican Lawyers.  aAmerican Revolution.  aAssociation of the Bar of the City of New York.  aCOVID-19 Pandemic Black Lives Matter.  aColonial America.  aDemocracy.  aDiversity, Equity, and Inclusion.  aInstitutional Economics.  aInsurrection.  aJacksonian Democracy.  aJames Madison.  aJustice Gap.  aLegal Tech.  aMulti-Racial Democracy.  aPeaceful Transition of Power.  aRule of Law.  aTammany Hall.  aU.S. Constitution & the Federalist Papers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075164240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479823703.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479823703423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479823703/original